18:00.200 --> 18:01.820
And here are your hosts.

18:06.120 --> 18:07.420
This is Daryl Lane.

18:07.800 --> 18:08.500
And David Crews.

18:08.500 --> 18:12.940
Jack Vance is one of the major talents that the field of fantasy and science fiction has produced.

18:13.280 --> 18:16.580
Tim Underwood, his friend and publisher, offers some reasons why.

18:17.440 --> 18:23.100
I think Jack has accomplished some things with some of his works that have just never been done before.

18:24.580 --> 18:27.640
Not only in terms of style, but in terms of feeling.

18:31.600 --> 18:35.380
He hearkens to a certain spirit, I think.

18:36.080 --> 18:45.580
A certain kind of person or certain kind of spirit is on his wavelength and responds strongly to his work.

18:47.960 --> 18:53.900
The latter part of his work and the best of his work is extremely well crafted.

18:54.120 --> 19:00.680
He's a craftsman, very well written, and accomplishes a lot of really unusual things in a very quiet way.

19:02.200 --> 19:03.960
Vance's accomplishments have been impressive.

19:04.580 --> 19:08.020
His science fiction career spans almost 40 years and began back in the pulp era.

19:08.600 --> 19:11.300
He's won the major awards for his science fiction and fantasy writer.

19:11.300 --> 19:17.100
One is the Hugo Award, awarded by readers, and the other is the Nebula Award, given by other writers.

19:17.860 --> 19:23.940
Some of his best known work includes The Dying Earth Stories, which go all the way back to his beginnings as a writer in the 40s,

19:24.200 --> 19:26.740
and more recently the five demon princes novels.

19:27.660 --> 19:29.500
Still, Vance hasn't received much recognition.

19:30.020 --> 19:31.120
We asked Underwood why.

19:32.360 --> 19:45.760
My feeling is that one responds strongly to Vance, one who feels much the same way about the world that he does.

19:46.120 --> 19:55.740
I think, why isn't he though as popular as, say, John Lai Corre, who I think people respond to in the same way?

19:55.740 --> 20:07.420
Well, Vance is more of a rarefied taste, I think, is the kind of things that he feels are important.

20:07.940 --> 20:16.980
The strangeness in the world about us and the unusual qualities of life itself, those kind of considerations are not important to a lot of people.

20:18.380 --> 20:24.420
People who do feel these things strongly are going to like Vance's rights.

20:24.820 --> 20:28.800
They're going to enjoy reading. They're going to enjoy the world that he's created.

20:29.760 --> 20:33.160
He's not done a lot of the things that make other writers successful.

20:33.820 --> 20:35.860
Like, he's never stayed with one character.

20:36.760 --> 20:50.900
The way that, say, Lai Corre stayed with Smiley, or the way that someone writes a Doc Savage novel 15 times in a row, or whatever.

20:51.780 --> 20:53.080
He hasn't done that.

20:53.740 --> 21:00.840
And he hasn't had one hero that he's repeated for any great number of books.

21:00.840 --> 21:14.140
And he hasn't had one contemporary theme that appeals to people like the battle of the sexes or something like that.

21:14.280 --> 21:15.520
Those aren't Jack's themes.

21:16.080 --> 21:24.000
Jack's considerations and themes are enormously subtle and kind of a rarefied nature.

21:24.320 --> 21:29.920
Vance has always been reluctant to discuss his own work or to offer any insights into his themes or intentions.

21:29.920 --> 21:31.800
Underwood suggests a reason.

21:59.920 --> 22:04.220
The rise of the overworld is the sequenced stories of the fellow Cougal.

22:05.400 --> 22:12.020
And that's partly because Cougal's a rascal, and Vance himself is a bit of a rascal.

22:13.760 --> 22:15.720
And Cougal's even more so.

22:15.900 --> 22:22.420
He's the kind of rascal that Vance would like to be if he wasn't such a nice guy at heart.

22:29.920 --> 22:38.480
